      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The bond between steel and concrete is primarily achieved through **mechanical interlock** and **chemical adhesion**. When rebar is placed in the concrete, the rough surface of the steel (often achieved through ribs or deformations) digs into the soft concrete matrix, creating a physical grip that resists slipping. Additionally, a chemical bond forms between the steel and the hydrated cement paste, further enhancing the connection.\n\nThis bond is critical because it ensures that when the concrete compresses and the steel stretches, they move together as a single unit. Without this bond, the steel would slip, and the structural integrity would fail. In some cases, **anchorage devices** like hooks or bends are added to the rebar ends to provide extra mechanical resistance against pull-out forces.\n\nSo, while the physics of the materials is sound, the practical implementation relies on these specific bonding mechanisms to ensure the steel and concrete work in harmony under load.",
